# Top
## Parsers
<pre>
FOAM includes parser libraries for both Java and Javascript.

They can be found in the foam.parse package.

The library provides a collection of what are called "parse combinators", which are simple
parsers which can be combined to form larger parsers. While this approach is unusual when
creating parsers, it is a proven technique in other domains, especially in GUI View libraries.
A large complex view like an email client or issue tracker is actually composed of simpler
views like buttons, text-fields, tab controls, etc. Parsers can be created by composing
simpler parsers, which are then themselves be composed into larger ones.

Parsers can be used anywhere a regular-expression could be, but are more powerful and can
be used in places where regular-expressions wouldn't be sufficient. Parsers are generally
not as compact as regular-expressions, but are easier to read.

Parsers can be used for many things, including:
1. extracting data from files
2. understanding network requests
3. validating and reformatting user input
4. creating languages, from small Domain-Specific-Languages (DSLs) to full-featured ones
5. source code linters, refactoring tools, or syntax highlighters

FOAM parsers accept input in the form of objects which implement the PStream interface.
PStream is short for "Parser Stream".


PStreams have the following interface:
    get int     pos   - The character position in the input stream.

    get Char    head  - The first character in the stream at the current position.

    get PStream tail  - A PStream for the next position in the input stream.

    get Object  value - 'Value' associated with this PStream.

    PStream setValue(Object value) - Creates a new PStream at the same position
        but with a new 'value'. The value is used to hold the result of a
        (sub-)parse.

PStreams are immutable, which greatly simplifies backtracking.

A Parser has the following interface:
    PStream parse(PStream stream);

It takes a PStream as input, and returns either a PStream
advanced to the point after all input is consumed by the parser,
or 'undefined' if the parse failed. The value generated by the parser
is stored in the .value property of the returned PStream.
</pre>
--

## Simple Parsers
First we'll start off by explaining the "simple" parsers. Simple parsers do not combine
any other parsers, they do all of their parsing on their own.
--

## foam.parse.Parsers
We use the foam.parse.Parsers Singleton class which provides convenience constructors
for the various parser types.
--

## Literal Parser
The simplest parser is a literal parser, which only parses the supplied string.
--
// Create a Singleton for accessing the built-in Parser library
var P = foam.parse.Parsers.create();

// Create an input PStream to parse our String
var ps = foam.parse.StringPStream.create({str: 'abcdef'});

// Let's look at our PStream
log(ps.toString());

// Now create a Literal Parser using the Singleton instance 'P' created above.
// This parser will only parse the literal 'abc'.
var lp = P.literal('abc');

// Now let's parse the PStream with the Parser
ps = lp.parse(ps);

// Now let's look at the results of our parsing
log(ps.toString());

// If we try to parse 'abc' again notice that it will fail because the stream is now
// at 'def', since 'abc' was consumed.
var np = lp.parse(ps);
log(!np?'undefined':np.toString());

// Here we'll create an in-lined literal 'def' parser and then call in directly.
log(P.literal('def').parse(ps).toString());

## Parser Tester
Before continuing, let's write a helper function testP() to make demonstrating parser examples easier.

The testP() function uses the U2 GUI library to create a table of input output pairs.
For more information on the U2 library, please view the U2 examples. For our purpose though,
you can treat this function as a blackbox that takes a parser and an array of strings to parse as input
and displays the results in a table
--
// Create a Singleton for accessing the built-in Parser library
const P = foam.parse.Parsers.create();

// Function that invokes the parser for the given array of strs
function testP(parser, strs) {
  globalThis.scope.br().start('table').
    style({'min-width': '90%'}).
    attrs({border: 1, cellpadding: 6, cellspacing: 0}).
    start('tr').start('th').
      style({background: '#eee'}).
      attrs({colspan:3}).add(`Parser: ${parser}`)
    .end().
  end().
  start('tr').
    start('th').
      add('Input').
    end().
    start('th').
      add('Parsed').
    end().
    start('th').
      add('Result').
    end().
  end().
  forEach(strs, function(str) {
    // create a mutable slot for the input, this way we can change our examples on the fly
    var inputSlot  = foam.lang.SimpleSlot.create({value: str});
    // create another mutable slot to hold the parser output
    var outputSlot = inputSlot.map(input => parser.parse(P.stringPStream(input)));

    this.start('tr').
      start('td').
        style({width:'25%'}).
        tag({class: 'foam.u2.TextField', size: 10, onKey: true, data$: inputSlot}).
      end().
      start('td').start('pre').
        add(outputSlot.map(output => output ? str.substring(0, output.pos) : '')).
      end().end().
      start('td').start('pre').
        style({color: outputSlot.map(output => output ? 'green' : 'red')}).
        add(outputSlot.map(output => output ? JSON.stringify(output.value) : 'undefined')).
      end().end().
    end();
  });
}

// Demonstrate the testP() function
testP(P.literal('abc'), [ 'abc', 'abcdef', 'Abc', 'ABC', 'xyz' ]);

// Store the test function and the singleton for the rest of the examples
globalThis.P = P;
globalThis.testP = testP;

## StringPStreams
There's also a convenience method for creating StringPStreams in foam.parse.Parsers.
Notice that the two StringPStreams appear identical, even though they are created in
different ways.
--
var ps = foam.parse.StringPStream.create({str: 'abc'});
log(ps.toString());

// Using the 'P' Singleton we created above.
log(P.stringPStream('abc').toString());


## Literal Ignore Case
The literalIC() parser is like literal(), that we saw earlier, but it performs a
case-insensitive match.
Notice that it also parses 'Abc' and 'ABC', whereas the literal() didn't.
--
testP(P.literalIC('abc'), [ 'abc', 'abcdef', 'Abc', 'ABC', 'xyz' ]);

## Any Char
The anyChar() parser is the most indiscriminating parser. It will parse any one character.
Notice that the only case where it fails to parse is when given an empty input.
--
testP(P.anyChar(), [ 'abc', 'ABC', '!@#$%', '' ]);

## EOF
EOF is a standard acronym for End Of File, but more generally it means the end of
any input source.
It is, in a way, the oppose of the anyChar() parser, since it won't parse any character
except the EOF.
--
testP(P.eof(), [ 'abc', 'ABC', '!@#$%', '' ]);

## Chars Parser
The chars() parser will parse any single character which is included as part of the
supplied string.
--
testP(P.chars('abc'), [ 'ax', 'bx', 'cx', 'xb', '' ]);

## Not Chars Parser
The notChars() parser will parse any single character which is NOT included as part of the
supplied string. However, it will not parse EOF.
--
testP(P.notChars('abc'), [ 'ax', 'bx', 'cx', 'xb', '' ]);

## Range Parser
The range() parser is similar to chars(), except that it lets you more easily specify a range of characters.
--
testP(P.range('0', '9'), [ 'a', '1', '2', '3', '9', 'z' ]);

// Is short form for:
testP(P.chars('0123456789'), [ 'a', '1', '2', '3', '9', 'z' ]);

// It is often used to detect numbers (like above) or letters, like:
testP(P.range('a', 'z'), [ 'a', '1', '2', '3', '9', 'z' ]);

// Notice that it still only matches a single character
testP(P.range('a', 'z'), [ 'abc', '123' ]);

## Combinators
The above parsers are all simple parsers. They all parse a single character or a literal string.
Now we'll look at combining the above simple parsers with parse combinators to create more complex parsers.
--

## Sequence Parser
The most common parse combinator is the sequence parser, which combines multiple parsers
into a single parser which only parses if each of the composed parsers successfully parses
in sequence. Each parser picks up where the previous parser left off in the input stream.
The sequence parser will fail if any of the composed parsers fails to parse.
On a successful parse, the returned value is an array of the parsed values of each
composed parser.
--
// The first parser accepts a letter and the second parser accepts a number.
var p = P.seq(P.range('a','z'), P.range('0','9'));
testP(p, [ 'r2', 'd2', '3p', 'xy' ]);

## Literal Parser Shortcut
In the example below, notice that we have three calls to P.literal(). Since P.literal() is so
commonly used when creating parsers, we make it the default when you just pass a String
to another parse combinator, like seq().
--
const TESTS = [ 'axxx', 'abxxx', 'abcxxx' ];

// The longer explicit method:
testP(P.seq(P.literal('a'), P.literal('b'), P.literal('c')), TESTS);

// A shorter more readable method:
testP(P.seq('a', 'b', 'c'), TESTS);


## String Parser
In one of the previous examples, when we demonstrated the sequence parser seq(), parsing 'r2' resulted
 in the parsed value of [ 'r', '2' ], an array. However, we often
want the result of our parsers to be string values, not the arrays of characters or
substrings that were parsed by the individual parsers that comprised the sequence parser.
To facilitate this, we use a very simple combinator parser called str() that decorates a single parser.
Instead of changing that delegate parser's behaviour, it just
changes its resulting value so that if it returns an array, it converts it into a single
string value with the array values concatenated.
--
// Notice unlike above, our results are strings, not arrays
var p = P.seq(P.range('a','z'), P.range('0','9'));
testP(P.str(p), [ 'r2', 'd2', '3p', 'xy' ]);

## Substring Parser
<pre>
The String parser shown above takes an array of parsed string values an concatenates them
into a single string return value. However, it is often the case that this isn't actually
what you want. Consider two cases where using str() is undesirable:
1. Sometimes you have multiple levels of string arrays and you would need to insert a str()
at each level.
2. You want to preserve input that has been lost, like the delimiters in a repeat().

Consider the following example which parses a sentence, which is a list of words separated
by whitespace. If you wanted to return the parsed string you would need to add a str()
around the 'word' parser so that you get strings instead of arrays of characters and then
you would need to add another str() around the repeat() in 'sentence'. But even this wouldn't
work because repeat() would have removed the whitespaces.

To solve this problem there is the substring() parse combinator which just returns the input
string that was parsed, as is, ignoring the return value of the composed parser.

???: perhaps input() would be a better name than substring()
</pre>
--
var   word       = P.str(P.plus(P.range('a','z')));
const whitespace = P.plus(' ');
const sentence   = P.repeat(word, whitespace);

const input = [ 'abc', 'abc def', 'abc   def   xyz' ];

// returns an array of words
testP(sentence, input);

// returns a single string of the words concatenated, without spaces
testP(P.str(sentence), input);

// preserves the original input
testP(P.substring(sentence), input);

// Notice that the str() on 'word' isn't needed when using substring().
var   word       = P.plus(P.range('a','z'));
testP(P.substring(sentence), input);


## Alternate Parser
The next most common parse combinator after the sequence parser, is the alt() parser.
It's job is to take multiple delgate parsers, just like seq(), but to succeed if any of them
succeed. It tries parsing with each composed parser in turn, and returns the result of the
first one that succeeds.
--
testP(P.alt(P.literal('A'), P.literal('B')), [ 'A', 'B', 'C' ]);

// Or just:

testP(P.alt('A', 'B'), [ 'A', 'B', 'C' ]);

## Repeat
The repeat() parser takes a single delegate parser and repeatedly uses it to parse
the input stream until it fails. The result of all delegate parses are combined in an array.

--
testP(P.repeat(P.range('0','9')), [ '1', '1x', '123xyz', 'abc' ]);

// Same example with the values converted into strings
testP(P.str(P.repeat(P.range('0','9'))), [ '1', '1x', '123xyz', 'abc' ]);

## Plus
You might have noticed that in the above example, repeat(0-9) succeeded in parsing the string 'abc' and provided an empty string result "" since there was no match. This is because repeat() parses zero or more occurrences of the delegate parser, so failure is a valid option. However, it's often the
case that you want to consider a repeated parser to have succeeded when it parses one or more
times. For this, there's the plus() parser, which behaves just like repeat(), but fails in
the case where the delegate parses 0 times.
--
testP(P.str(P.plus(P.range('0','9'))), [ '1', '1x', '123xyz', 'abc' ]);

## Delimited Repeat
It's common to want to use repeat() to parse some pattern where each entry is separated
by some other pattern. Examples include a comma separated list or semi-colon separated
program statements. While you could do this by including the delimiter with seq() in the
delegate parser, this is so common an operation that repeat supports it directly.
--
// First lets' look how we would parse a comma delimited list of letters without using this feature:
testP(
  P.str(P.repeat(P.str(P.seq(P.range('a','z'), P.literal(','))))),
  [ 'a', 'a,b', 'a,b,c', 'a,b,c,'
]);


// Notice that the above never parsed the last letter, except for the last case: 'a,b,c,'
// because there's a bug in our parser. We only want the comma between letters, not after,
// which prevents the last 'c' from being parsed.
// To fix this, we need to make our parser more complicated:
testP(
  P.str(P.seq(P.str(P.repeat(P.str(P.seq(P.range('a','z'), P.literal(','))))), P.range('a', 'z'))),
  [ 'a', 'a,b', 'a,b,c', 'a,b,c,'
]);

// This fixes that problem, but our parser is getting more complicated. Also,
// notice that it is including the commas in the parsed output, but we probably
// just want the letters.
// The solution is to specify the delimiter to repeat():
testP(
  P.str(P.repeat(P.range('a','z'), ',')),
  [ '', 'a', 'a,b', 'a,b,c', 'a,b,c,'
]);

// By supplying the delimiter parser as the second argument to repeat(), it knows that we
// only want to skip delimiters between values and it excludes them from the output.
// It is also shorter and easier to understand than our first attempt.

// You can also specify a delimiter parser with plus(), in cases where you only want
// the parse to succeed when you have one or more parses.
testP(
 P.str(P.plus(P.range('a','z'), ',')),
  [ '', 'a', 'a,b', 'a,b,c', 'a,b,c,'
]);

## Repeat with a Number of Repetitions
The repeat() parses zero or more times and plus() repeats one or more times, but sometimes
you want to parse with some minimum number of repeats other than zero or one.
The third optional argument of repeat() let's you specify just that.
Since the second argument is the delimiter parser, if you don't want
to have a delimiter, pass 'undefined' as its value.

The below example checks passwords to ensure that they're at least five characters long.
Notice that the repeat() parser still continues until it fails, hence for the last sample
it repeated six times, meaning that the specified repeat parameter is the miniumum number
of repetitions not the absolute limit.
--
testP(
  P.str(P.repeat(P.alt(P.range('a','z'), P.range('A', 'Z'), P.range('0', '9'), P.anyChar('!@#$%^&*')), undefined, 5)),
  [ 's', 's@', 's@c', 's@C&', 's@C&t', 's@C&t1' ]
);

## Not Parser
The Not parser is unusual in that it suceeds only if it's delegate parser fails.
--
var quote        = P.literal('"');
var stringBody   = P.str(P.repeat(P.not(quote, P.anyChar())));
var stringParser = P.seq(quote, stringBody, quote);
testP(P.str(stringParser), [ '""', '"a"', '"abc13234$@#$"', '"abc"asfasdf"' ]);

## Seq1 Parser
Notice that in the previous string parser example, our result value was an array where
the first and last elements were the quote '"' characters, and the second element
was the actual string value we wanted. We would like the output value to ignore the
surrounding syntax and just return us the one inner value that we're interested in.
This is common enough to warrant it's own parse combinator. Seq1 behaves just like the regular
seq() parser except instead of returning an array of values parsed by the delegates, it only
returns the return value of one parser, the index of which you specify as the first argument.
By using seq1(1, ...) instead of seq(...) we tell the parser to ignore the quote parsers and
just give us the result of the stringBody parser, which is at location 1 (starting at zero).
--
var quote        = P.literal('"');
var stringBody   = P.str(P.repeat(P.not(quote, P.anyChar())));
var stringParser = P.seq1(1, quote, stringBody, quote);
testP(stringParser, [ '""', '"a"', '"abc13234$@#$"', '"abc"asfasdf"' ]);

## Until Parser
The string pattern in the above example combined repeat(), not(), and anyChar() in order to extract the string.
This pattern is common enough that we have a special parser for that called until().
It parses input until the delegated parser matches.
We can use it to simplify the above stringParser.
--
var quote        = P.literal('"');
var stringParser = P.str(P.seq1(1, quote, P.until(quote)));
testP(stringParser, [ '""', '"a"', '"abc13234$@#$"', '"abc"asfasdf"' ]);

## Optional Parser
The optional() parser composes a single delegate parser and if that parser parses, then it returns
its result, otherwise it returns the PStream as is, without failing. This lets parsing
continue from the same point.
--
testP(P.seq(P.optional('header'), 'body'),
  [ 'headerbody', 'body', 'header' ]
);

## Example
The following example uses optional() several times to create a phone number parser where
the long distance '1', the area code, and some punctuation are all optional.
Notice that the parser also uses the str() combinator in several spots to ensure the final
output is a string rather than an array.
Notice this line: P.optional(P.literal('-'), '-'),
We can specify a second parameter to optional() that returns the value to be used if the parser
doesn't parse. In this case, we just want the add '-' if it wasn't present, to standardize
the output format of the parser.
--

var digit    = P.range('0', '9');
var areaCode = P.str(P.seq('(', digit, digit, digit, ')'));
var phoneNumber = P.str(P.seq(
  P.optional('1'),
  P.optional(' '),
  P.optional(areaCode),
  P.optional(' ', ' '),
  P.str(P.seq(digit, digit, digit)),
  P.optional('-', '-'),
  P.str(P.seq(digit, digit, digit, digit))
));

testP(phoneNumber, [
  '1 (555) 555-1234',
  '1(555) 555-1234',
  '(555) 555-1234',
  '(555)555-1234',
  '555-1234',
  '5551234'
]);

## Optimizations
## Repeat0
<pre>
Some parsers end with the suffix '0'. This means they are specialized to not return any
value. This may seem unnecessary, and from a strict feature point of view, it is, but
the advantage of this type of parser is that it is more efficient because it performs
less work and generates less garbage. Parser performance can be very important because
it is often the most expensive operation performed by many applications.

In this example we use the repeat0() parser to parse whitespace. We don't care about
the whitespace, so we don't really care about the size or formation of the whitespace
and just want to skip over it efficiently. This is common for programming languages
where a significant portion of the input may be whitespace, and yet we don't need to extract
any values from the whitespace. We just want to skip over it as quickly and efficiently
as possible.
</pre>
--
const whitespace = P.repeat0(P.chars(' \t\n'), null, 1);
const word       = P.str(P.plus(P.range('a', 'z')));
const words      = P.repeat(word, whitespace);

testP(words, [
  'abc',
  'word word   abc     xyz',
  `word    word
   on another line
   and more
  `
]);

## Seq0 and Until0
Just as repeat0() is the no-value version of repeat(), seq0() is the no-value version of seq() and until0() is the no-value version of until().
We use both seq0() and until0() in this example to parse C-style /* comments */. For a language compiler we might throw away the contents of
comments, so this type of parser might make sense.
--
var comment = P.seq0('/*', P.until0('*/'));
testP(comment, [ '/* This is a comment. Ignore the results. */' ]);

// If you wanted the comment contents, then you would do:

var comment = P.seq1(1, '/*', P.str(P.until('*/')));
testP(comment, [ "/* This is a comment. Don't ignore the results. */" ]);


## Example: Boolean
Consider the following simple parser which is meant to parse boolean true or false values:
--
var booleanParser1 = P.alt('true', 'false');
testP(booleanParser1, [ 'true', 'false' ]);

// The above booleanParser1 works, but isn't ideal because the values it returns are
// the string values "true" and "false", but since we are parsing booleans, we would
// probably prefer getting back the actual boolean true and false values (ie. actual booleans
// not strings).

// This second version is almost the same but it specifies a second optional argument
// to literal() which substitutes the value to be returned instead of the specified
// string literal, in the event that the parse succeeds.


var booleanParser2 = P.alt(P.literal('true', true), P.literal('false', false));
testP(booleanParser2, [ 'true', 'false' ]);

// Now we get actual true and false values rather than "true" and "false".

## Grammars: Parenthesis Matching
<pre>
All of the above examples could have also been done with regular-expressions, but this
is the first example of something which can be parsed by a general-purpose parser but
could not be parsed with a regular-expression.

In this example we detect if a group of parenthesis is matched. To do so, the definition
needs to be recursive, which cannot be done with regular expressions. Notice that the
definition of 'parens' makes reference to itself with the sym('parens') parser.

When making recursive or more complex parsers, it is common to combine the individual
parsers into what is called a 'Grammar'. A grammar is a collection of mutually recursive
named parsers which together form a higher-level parser. A grammar is similar to how
many methods are combined in a single class in OO programming. Because grammars and OO
classes are so similar, FOAM uses classes to represent grammars.

To create a Grammar, you create a foam.CLASS which extends 'foam.parse.Grammar' and then
create a 'grammar' method which returns the grammar as JS map. The name you give each
parser in the map you return is called its symbol name. In the example below these are 'START' and 'parens'.
You reference a named parser using the sym() parser, like sym('parens'), in the example.
In that case, it is referencing itself. The symbol named 'START' is special because it
represents the default top-level parser for your grammar. When we use the MatchedParensParser,
it is the START parser which is used.

Notice that any of the parsers described previously are made available to the grammar
method as parameters. This is done to minimize syntax and make the resulting grammar easier
to read.

Parser grammars are normally defined in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_Backus%E2%80%93Naur_form">Extended Backus–Naur form (EBNF)</a>, which is similar
enough to FOAM Grammars to make conversion easy.

</pre>
--
foam.CLASS({
  name: 'MatchedParensParser',
  extends: 'foam.parse.Grammar',

  methods: [
    function grammar(str, sym, eof, repeat, seq, seq1) {
      return {
        START: seq1(0, sym('parens'), eof()),

        // The 'repeat' allows for ()'s to be side-by-side, like ()() or (()())
        parens: str(repeat(
          str(seq('(', sym('parens'), ')')),
        ))
      };
    }
  ]
});

var p = MatchedParensParser.create();

testP(p, [
  // Matched
  '', '()', '(())', '()()', '((())()(()))',
  // Unmatched
  ')(', '(()', '())'
]);



## Grammars: Phone Number Parser
While the above Grammar had only a single rule 'parens', it is more common for a grammar
to have multiple rules, as in this example which implements a telephone number parser.
--
foam.CLASS({
  name: 'PhoneNumberParser',
  extends: 'foam.parse.Grammar',

  methods: [
    function grammar(alt, sym, seq1, seq, str, literal, optional, plus, range) {
      return {
        START: str(seq(
          optional(sym('countryCode')),
          alt(
            str(seq(sym('areaCode'), optional(' ', ' '), sym('simple'))),
            sym('simple'))
        )),

        simple: str(seq(sym('prefix'), optional(sym('separator'), '-'), sym('line'))),

        digit: range('0', '9'),

        countryCode: seq1(1, optional('+'), literal('1', '1 '), optional(' ')),

        areaCode: str(seq(
          optional('(', '('),
          sym('digit'), sym('digit'), sym('digit'),
          optional(')', ')'))),

        prefix: str(seq( sym('digit'), sym('digit'), sym('digit') )),

        separator: alt('-', ' '),

        line: str(seq( sym('digit'), sym('digit'), sym('digit'), sym('digit') ))
      };
    }
  ]
});

var p = PhoneNumberParser.create();

// A good way to test/debug Grammars to to test each symbol individually:

testP(p.getSymParser('countryCode'), [ '', '1', '+1', '+1 ' ]);
testP(p.getSymParser('areaCode'),    [ '', '555', '(555)', '55' ]);
testP(p.getSymParser('prefix'),      [ '', '12', '123', '1234' ]);
testP(p.getSymParser('line'),        [ '', '123', '1234', '12345' ]);

testP(p, [
  '+1 (555) 555-1234',
  '1 (555) 555-1234',
  '1(555) 555-1234',
  '(555) 555-1234',
  '555 555-1234',
  '15555551234',
  '5555551234',
  '(555)555-1234',
  '555-1234',
  '5551234'
]);

## Semantic Actions
<pre>
So far all of our parsers have mostly just returned the matched input but haven't actually
converted the input into anything else. While this is what is commonly done with
regular-expressions, parsers typically convert the input into something useful.
For an example a parser for the language 'C' might convert the source code input
into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) that is used by later stages of the compiler,
or a calculator expression parser might convert an arithmetic expression into
the result of that calculation.

This is done by what are called "Semantic Actions", which are just map functions which
are applied to the parser result to transform it into some other value.

Below is a very simple example which only adds one semantic action to our Grammar.
In this case it adds an action to the 'number' symbol so that numbers are converted
to actual JS numbers, rather than being left as Strings.

Semantic Actions are defined by creating a method named &lt;SymbolName&gt;Action. So in this
example, the 'numberAction' method is applied to results parsed by the 'number' parser.
</pre>
--

foam.CLASS({
  name: 'VersionParser',
  extends: 'foam.parse.Grammar',

  methods: [
    function grammar(alt, not, sym, seq, str, optional, plus, repeat, range, anyChar) {
      return {
        START: repeat(sym('component'), optional(sym('separator'))),

        component: alt(sym('number'), sym('string')),

        digit: range('0', '9'),

        number: str(plus(sym('digit'))),

        string: str(plus(not(alt(sym('digit'), sym('separator')), anyChar()))),

        separator: alt('.', '-')
      };
    },

    function numberAction(v) { return parseInt(v); }
  ]
});


var p = VersionParser.create();

testP(p, [ '1', '1.1', '1.1b', '3.14159-26b' ]);

## Email Address Parser
The following parser uses two semantic actions to parse email addresses which can be
either simple like "john@email.com" or labelled like "John Doe &lt;john@email.com&gt;".
--
foam.CLASS({
  name: 'EmailAddressParser',
  extends: 'foam.parse.Grammar',

  methods: [
    function grammar(alt, sym, seq, str, repeat, notChars) {
      return {
        START: sym('address'),

        addressList: repeat(sym('address'), seq(',', repeat(' '))),

        address: alt(sym('labelledAddress'), sym('simpleAddress')),

        labelledAddress: seq(repeat(notChars('<,')), '<', sym('simpleAddress'), '>'),

        simpleAddress: seq(repeat(notChars('@')), '@', repeat(notChars('\r>,')))
      };
    },

    function labelledAddressAction(v) { return v[0].join('') + v[1] + v[2] + v[3]; },

    function simpleAddressAction(v) { return v[0].join('') + v[1] + v[2].join(''); }
  ]
});

var p = EmailAddressParser.create();

testP(p, [ 'John Doe<john@email.com>', 'john@email.com' ]);

// Notice we also added an 'addressList' rule to the grammar, which is useful:
testP(p.getSymParser('addressList'), [ 'john@email.com', 'john@email.com,jane@email.com' ]);

## Match and MatchAll
<pre>
Usually parsers consume the entire input, but they can also be used like regexes to find
one or multiple instances in a larger input. Calling .match() on a Grammar will find the first
instance in the input text, whereas matchAll() will return an array of all matches.

The following example uses the previous PhoneNumberParser to extract one or more phone numbers
from an input text.
</pre>
--
var p = PhoneNumberParser.create();
var input = 'blah blah blah (555) 123-4556, +1 (555) 123-1234 blah blah blah 555-1234  blah blah';
log('One:', p.match(input));
log('All:', p.matchAll(input).join(', '));

## Grammar Reuse
<pre>
Typical parser generators like YACC (Yet Another Compiler Compiler) do not offer very good
mechanisms for reuse, but Object-Oriented (OO) programmers are used to having <b>inheritance</b> and <b>composition</b>
for this purpose. Inheritance allows a class to derive properties and behavior from a parent class,
enabling code reuse and specialization. Composition, on the other hand, involves building complex
functionality by combining simpler, independent components, promoting modularity and flexibility.

FOAM Grammars nicely bring the worlds of high-level parser specifications and OO together,
so that you can have the advantages of modern OO languages while writing your grammars.

This example demonstrates reuse through both composition and inheritance. The example is of a
simple expression parser and interpreter derived from the built-in base defined in:
<a href="https://github.com/foam-framework/foam/blob/2966cde661ccadbb8b1548fede78f6d67cc53ed5/core/experimental/scaleParser.js">scaleParser.js</a>.

For <b>composition</b>, we create a NumberParser which is only able to parse negative or positive
integers. This class/grammar isn't very large, but by the time we add support for
decimal places, exponents, and maybe even numbers expressed in different bases, this class
could become fairly large. It makes the code more modular and reusable to keep isolated
features in their own classes. This way we could reuse the NumberParser in other classes,
or could have different versions (say a JS version or a Java version) and then
choose between implementations if we wanted to support JS or Java style
numbers.

To illustrate <b>inheritance</b>, we first create a generic ExpressionParser, and then we inherit from
it to create an ExpressionInterpreter. Grammars can be large and complex, and represent
a sizeable investment of effort, so you might want to use the same grammar for multiple
purposes. For example, our ExpressionParser might be used for an expression linter, pretty-printer,
interpreter (as we've done), JS compiler (compile to JS syntax), Java compiler, etc.

As an example, imagine you were writing a tool that linted both EcmaScript versions 14 and 15.
These too languages are mostly the same, but not identical. You could write two separate
parsers and linters, or you could use inheritance and composition to reuse most of the code,
keeping your codebase smaller and more maintainable. And then when the next version of
EcmaScript comes, your could quickly add support by reusing the code and parsers you already have.

This example is also interesting because it demonstrates a common use of parsers, which is
creating languages. Implementing a new language might seem like some kind of
deep magic, but as you can see in this example, the basic concept isn't difficult.
While we just create a simple expression interpreter, the same techniques
could be used to make a full fledged language interpreter.
</pre>
--

const input = [
  '123',       // number
  '-123',      // number
  '(123)',     // group
  'sqrt(9)',   // fun
  'log2(64)',  // fun
  'x',         // variable
  'y',         // variable
  'z',         // variable
  '1+2',       // expr
  '1+2+3',     // expr
  '1*2',       // expr1
  '2^4',       // expr2
  '1*(x+y*sqrt(9))*-23/4',
  'abc'        // bad input
];

// A simple parser for negative or positive integers
foam.CLASS({
  name: 'NumberParser',
  extends: 'foam.parse.Grammar',

  methods: [
    function grammar(plus, sym, alt, seq1, range, str) { return {
      START: alt(sym('positive'), sym('negative')),

      positive: str(plus(range('0', '9'))),

      negative: seq1(1, '-', sym('positive'))
    }; },

    function positiveAction(s) { return parseInt(s); },

    function negativeAction(n) { return -n; }
  ]
});


// A generic Expression Parser. It will just tell you if the expression is valid,
// but does not do anything to evaluate it.
foam.CLASS({
  name: 'ExpressionParser',
  extends: 'foam.parse.Grammar',

  requires: [ 'NumberParser' ],

  methods: [
    function grammar(plus, sym, alt, opt, seq, seq1, lit, range, eof) { return {
      START: seq1(0, sym('expr'), eof()),

      expr: seq(sym('expr1'), opt(seq(alt('+', '-'), sym('expr')))),

      expr1: seq(sym('expr2'), opt(seq(alt('*', '/'), sym('expr1')))),

      expr2: seq(sym('expr3'), opt(seq1(1, '^', sym('expr2')))),

      expr3: alt(
        sym('fun'),
        sym('variable'),
        sym('number'),
        sym('group')),

      variable: alt('x', 'y', 'z'),

      fun: seq(
        alt('sqrt', 'log2'), '(', sym('expr'), ')'
      ),

      group: seq1(1, '(', sym('expr'), ')'),

      number: this.NumberParser.create()
    }; }
  ]
});

const p = ExpressionParser.create();

testP(p, input);

// An Expression interpreter. Extends the parser above to implement an interpreter/calculator
// which evaluates the supplied expressions.
foam.CLASS({
  name: 'ExpressionInterpreter',
  extends: 'ExpressionParser',

  properties: [ 'x', 'y', 'z' ],

  methods: [
    function exprAction(v) {
      if ( v[1] === null ) return v[0];
      if ( v[1][0] == '+' ) return v[0] + v[1][1];
      return v[0] - v[1][1];
    },
    function expr1Action(v) {
      if ( v[1] === null ) return v[0];
      if ( v[1][0] == '*' ) return v[0] * v[1][1];
      return v[0] / v[1][1];
    },
    function expr2Action(v) {
      if ( v[1] === null ) return v[0];
      return Math.pow(v[0], v[1]);
    },
    function funAction(v) {
      return v[0] == 'sqrt' ?
        Math.sqrt(v[2]) :
        Math.log2(v[2]) ;
    },
    function variableAction(v) { return this[v]; }
  ]
});

const interp = ExpressionInterpreter.create({x: 1, y: 10, z: 100});

testP(interp, input);

// We could extend ExpressionParser again to implement a pretty-printer or a compiler

## Another Reuse Example
Imagine we wanted to create a calculator for working with binary numbers. Rather than
starting from scratch, we can reuse our existing ExpressionInterpreter and just swap
out the default decimal NumberParser with a new BinaryNumberParser.
--
const input = [
  '1',         // number
  '0',         // number
  '-101',      // number
  '(101)',     // group
  '1+10',      // addition
  '10*100',    // addition
  '101+111+1'  // addition
];

foam.CLASS({
  name: 'BinaryNumberParser',
  extends: 'foam.parse.Grammar',

  methods: [
    function grammar(plus, sym, alt, seq1, range, str) { return {
      START: alt(sym('positive'), sym('negative')),

      positive: str(plus(range('0', '1'))),

      negative: seq1(1, '-', sym('positive'))
    }; },

    function positiveAction(s) { return parseInt(s, 2); },

    function negativeAction(n) { return -n; }
  ]
});

foam.CLASS({
  name: 'BinaryInterpreter',
  extends: 'ExpressionInterpreter',
  requires: [ 'BinaryNumberParser as NumberParser' ]
});

const interp = BinaryInterpreter.create({x: 1, y: 10, z: 100});
testP(interp, input);

## Error Reporting
<pre>
All of the examples until now have simply returned undefined if the input could not be
parsed, but it would be much better to be able to report an error message which
explained why the input could not be parsed. We do this with the ErrorReportingPStream.

Recall that PStream is an interface, but notice that the StringPStream is the
only implementation that we've seen so far. The ErrorReportingPStream is a PStream
decorator that wraps another PStream (probably a StringPStream in JS) and figures
out where a parse error occurred and provides an error message explaining where the
parse failed and what was expected.
</pre>
--
// TODO: The JS ErrorReportingPStream isn't as useful as the Java version and should be improved
// TODO: finish this example
